        The morning came fast.  I had barely cracked open an eye in my hotel room when I noticed that I was going to be late for my meeting with Mechanical's executive team unless I skipped one part of my morning routine.  <br/> <br/>I chose shaving.  I certainly wasn't going to be missing my cup of coffee at the nearby Starbucks.  Pashaw.<br/><br/>I made record time in traffic, and appeared in front of Mechanical's receptionist with two minutes to spare.  <br/><br/>Plainclothes security escorted me again into the elevator.  It was like being a movie star, only without the movies, the money or the star status.<br/><br/>I couldn't stop thinking about my investigation, about Janice, and about the briefing I was about to give the Mechanical team.    The CCTV clearly showed Janice inserting what appeared to be a blank CD-R into her laptop - but I had to PROVE that she transferred files onto the CD-R.  By the results of my findings, I could not tell them that Janice burned the files onto a CD-R.<br/><br/>And then suddenly, it hit me...<br/>Years of working with linux and command-line CD-burning software flashed before my eyes as an idea smashed its way into my cranial cavity.   <br/><br/>I apologized to the Corporate Security personnel and asked if I could return to the reception level.  I then informed the receptionist that my meeting would need to be delayed until after lunch time.  <br/><br/>I quickly drove back to my hotel, whipped Roscoe out from the trunk and entered my room.  After a few minutes, Roscoe was up and running and I was examining the file system of the laptop one more time.  <br/><br/>What was I looking for?  Application swap.  Almost all CD-burning applications write the destination CD image to a swap image (most of these are ISO files) before burning to a CD-R to prevent problems with the burn.   I had looked the application directory and subdirectories up and down, but hadn't found anything interesting - but we're talking Windows here.   Time to bet some money that the application developer had decided to use the system 'temp' directory.   Most of the time, I'd be looking in C:\WINDOWS\TEMP, however the laptop image notes that Mechanical's Data Security folks had given me showed that the system temporary directory was set to C:\TMP.<br/><br/>Glancing through C:\TMP, there were lots of files - and a quick sort by date showed me  three files that still retained the mystery date that Janice had supposedly burned the CD-R.  I had seen these files before during my intial investigations, but I couldn't make sense of the file structure - it looked like one large binary file.  <br/><br/>Taking a gamble, I exported the file from the image and burned it onto a CDR.  Throwing the CD-R into my linux laptop, I mounted the file using the loopback device to /mnt/image.   My pulse quickened as I changed into the /mnt/image directory and issued the standard 'ls -la' command.  <br/><br/>Paydirt.<br/><br/>The 'binary file' was actually an ISO image that was created by the application shortly before the burn process.  All of the filenames and filesizes that Mechanical had provided me matched the directory listing to a proverbial ' T '.<br/><br/>My meeting with the Mechanical management team was going to be quite different than initially anticipated.<br/><br/>Management team mangled by clue banana.  News at 11.<br/>
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer marginleftgutter">
            <hr/>
    <table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
        <tr>
            <td>
                <div style="margin-right: 9px; float: left; height: 60px; width: 60px" lazysource="http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/s_610000.jpg"></div>
